/**
\page org_mitk_views_m2_data M2aia Data View and Data Tools View

\tableofcontents

\section m2data_overview Overview

The <b>Data View</b> and the <b>Data Tools View</b> are the two central control panels for working
with mass spectrometry imaging (MSI) datasets in M2aia.  Open them via
<em>Window &rarr; Show View</em> or the perspective toolbar.

- The <b>Data View</b> controls how ion images are generated and which signal-processing
  steps are applied before pixels are rendered.
- The <b>Data Tools View</b> provides dataset-level utilities: level-window equalisation,
  mosaic / tiling layout, image alignment, and a colour-bar annotation.

\section m2data_dataview Data View

\subsection m2data_dataview_ionimage Creating an Ion Image

An ion image is a 2-D map in which every pixel shows the aggregated signal intensity
within a user-defined m/z window centred on a target mass.

\note Ion images are only generated for MSI datasets that are currently <b>visible</b>
(check mark enabled) in the Data Manager.  Datasets that are hidden are silently
skipped.  Toggle the eye / check-box icon next to a node in the Data Manager to
include or exclude it from image generation.

\subsubsection m2data_dataview_ionimage_manual Manual entry via the Data View

-# Enter the target m/z value in the <b>m/z</b> spin box.
-# Set the mass tolerance in the <b>Tolerance</b> spin box and choose whether the
   unit is <b>Da</b> (absolute) or <b>PPM</b> (parts per million, relative).
-# Press <b>Create Image</b> to generate the ion image for all visible datasets.

\subsubsection m2data_dataview_ionimage_spectrum Interaction via the Spectrum View

The Spectrum View and the Data View are tightly coupled.  Any action in the spectrum
chart that selects an m/z position automatically triggers a new ion image for all
visible datasets.

<b>Mouse interactions</b>

| Gesture | Effect |
|---------|--------|
| <b>Double-click</b> inside the chart | Requests a new ion image at the clicked m/z position.  The tolerance from the Data View is used. |
| <b>Double-click</b> below the x-axis area | Resets the x-axis to the full data range. |
| <b>Double-click</b> left of the y-axis area | Resets the y-axis to its auto range. |
| <b>Alt + left-click and drag</b> | Range selection: press <em>Alt</em> and drag across a spectral region.  On release, the centre and half-width of the selected interval are sent to the Data View as m/z and tolerance, and a new ion image is generated immediately. |
| <b>Middle-button drag</b> | Pan the chart horizontally without triggering an image update. |
| <b>Scroll wheel</b> (inside chart) | Zoom the x-axis around the cursor position. |
| <b>Ctrl + scroll wheel</b> | Faster zoom (3.5× factor). |
| <b>Scroll wheel below x-axis</b> | Zoom the x-axis only. |
| <b>Scroll wheel left of y-axis</b> | Zoom the y-axis only. |

<b>Keyboard shortcuts</b> (active while the Spectrum View panel has focus)

| Shortcut | Effect |
|----------|--------|
| <b>Shift + →</b> | Step to the next m/z position (centre + one tolerance window) and update the ion image.  Jumps over data gaps automatically. |
| <b>Shift + ←</b> | Step to the previous m/z position (centre − one tolerance window). |
| <b>Shift + ↑</b> | Increase the current tolerance by 10 % and update the ion image. |
| <b>Shift + ↓</b> | Decrease the current tolerance by 10 % and update the ion image. |
| <b>Ctrl + →</b> | Jump to the next centroid peak from a loaded peak list and update the ion image. |
| <b>Ctrl + ←</b> | Jump to the previous centroid peak from a loaded peak list. |

When stepping with <b>Shift + ←/→</b>, if the candidate m/z lands inside a gap between
data ranges (e.g. between two imzML datasets with non-overlapping mass axes), the
cursor automatically jumps to the boundary of the nearest valid range so no step is
wasted on a position that would produce an empty image.

\subsection m2data_dataview_pipeline Signal Processing Pipeline

Every time an ion image is created, the following processing steps are applied to each
spectrum in the order listed below.

\subsubsection m2data_pp_normalization 1 – Spectral Normalization

Corrects for pixel-to-pixel differences in total ion abundance so that intensity values
are comparable across pixels.  Normalization is applied first, to raw intensities,
before any further spectral processing.

| Option | Description |
|--------|-------------|
| <b>None</b> | Raw intensities are used. |
| <b>TIC</b> | Total ion current – each spectrum is divided by the sum of all its intensities. |
| <b>RMS</b> | Root-mean-square – each spectrum is divided by its RMS value. |
| <b>Mean</b> | Each spectrum is divided by its mean intensity. |
| <b>Median</b> | Each spectrum is divided by its median intensity. |
| <b>InFile</b> | Uses a pre-computed normalization vector stored in the imzML binary data. |

Normalization images (one per pixel) are computed on demand and can be shown in the
Data Manager by ticking the corresponding <em>Show &lt;type&gt; normalization image</em>
check box in the <b>Settings</b> section of the Data View.

\warning <b>Centroid data and spectrum-based normalization:</b> Options such as
<b>TIC</b>, <b>RMS</b>, <b>Mean</b>, and <b>Median</b> compute normalization factors
from the intensities present in each spectrum.  For <em>centroid</em> datasets (processed
centroid or continuous centroid) only the detected peaks are stored, so the computed
factor reflects only those peaks rather than the full spectral signal.  This can lead to
misleading or inconsistent normalization results.  When working with centroid data it is
strongly recommended to use <b>None</b> or to provide a pre-computed per-pixel
normalization vector via an external file. Further details can be found in the section
\ref m2data_artifacts "External Data and Auto-Loading".

\subsubsection m2data_pp_smoothing 2 – Spectral Smoothing

Reduces high-frequency noise in each spectrum after normalization.

| Option | Description |
|--------|-------------|
| <b>None</b> | No smoothing. |
| <b>Gaussian</b> | Convolution with a Gaussian kernel. |
| <b>SavitzkyGolay</b> | Polynomial least-squares smoothing. |

The <b>Smoothing Half-Window</b> spin box controls the kernel half-width (number of
data points on each side of the centre).

\subsubsection m2data_pp_baseline 3 – Baseline Correction

Removes the slowly varying baseline signal that underlies the peaks.

| Option | Description |
|--------|-------------|
| <b>None</b> | No baseline correction. |
| <b>TopHat</b> | Morphological top-hat filter; robust for dense spectra. |
| <b>Median</b> | Rolling median baseline. |

The <b>Baseline Half-Window</b> spin box controls the filter half-width.  Larger values
produce a flatter, broader baseline estimate.

\subsubsection m2data_pp_transformation 4 – Intensity Transformation

Applies a point-wise function to every intensity value after baseline correction.

| Option | Description |
|--------|-------------|
| <b>None</b> | No transformation. |
| <b>Log2</b> | Base-2 logarithm: \f$ I' = \log_2(I + 1) \f$. |
| <b>SquareRoot</b> | Square root: \f$ I' = \sqrt{I} \f$. |

\subsubsection m2data_pp_pooling 5 – Range Pooling (Ion Image Aggregation)

Defines how intensities within the tolerance window [\f$ m/z - \delta,\; m/z + \delta \f$]
are combined into a single pixel value.

| Option | Description |
|--------|-------------|
| <b>Mean</b> | Arithmetic mean over all data points in the window (default). |
| <b>Sum</b> | Sum of all data points. |
| <b>Maximum</b> | Maximum data point. |
| <b>Median</b> | Median of all data points. |

\subsubsection m2data_pp_imgnorm 6 – Image-Level Normalization

After the ion image has been assembled, an optional spatial rescaling is applied across all pixels.

| Option | Description |
|--------|-------------|
| <b>None</b> | No rescaling. |
| <b>zScore</b> | Standardize pixel values: subtract the mean and divide by the standard deviation (z-score normalization). |
| <b>MinMax</b> | Scale pixel values to the [0, 1] range using the minimum and maximum of the image. |
| <b>ParetoScaling</b> | Divide each pixel by the square root of the standard deviation (Pareto scaling). |
| <b>VastScaling</b> | Variance-stabilizing scaling: divide by the standard deviation and scale by the coefficient of variation. |
| <b>RangeScaling</b> | Divide each pixel by the range (max − min) of the image. |

\subsubsection m2data_pp_imgsmoothing 7 – Image-Level Smoothing

A spatial smoothing filter applied to the final ion image.

| Option | Description |
|--------|-------------|
| <b>None</b> | No spatial smoothing. |
| <b>Gaussian</b> | 2-D Gaussian blur. |

\subsection m2data_dataview_settings Settings Panel

The collapsible <b>Settings</b> section at the bottom of the Data View contains
checkboxes that toggle the visibility of derived helper nodes in the Data Manager:

- <b>Show index image</b> – The pixel-index image that maps each valid spectrum
  position to its storage index in the imzML binary file.
- <b>Show mask image</b> – The tissue mask that defines which pixels contain valid
  spectra.
- <b>Show &lt;type&gt; normalization image</b> – One checkbox per normalization
  strategy (TIC, RMS, …).  When activated, M2aia computes the corresponding
  normalisation image if it has not been computed yet and makes it visible in the
  Data Manager for inspection or export.

\section m2data_toolsview Data Tools View

\subsection m2data_tools_lw Level Window Equalisation

Select a reference image in the <b>Reference image</b> combo box and press
<b>Equalize LW</b> to copy its level-window setting to every image that is
currently in the Data Manager.  This is useful when comparing multiple ion
images side by side: setting one image's contrast and propagating it to all
others makes brightness differences immediately visible.

\subsection m2data_tools_tiling Image Tiling (Mosaic Layout)

When several datasets are loaded, they may have overlapping spatial origins.
The tiling functions rearrange them into a grid for simultaneous inspection.

- Set the number of rows in the <b>Mosaic rows</b> spin box.
- Press <b>Apply Tiling</b> to arrange all <em>visible</em> images into a grid.
  Images are sorted alphabetically by node name and placed row by row.  Each
  cell is sized to the largest image in the dataset so that no image is cropped.
- Press <b>Reset Tiling</b> to restore every image to the origin coordinates
  stored in the imzML metadata (IMS:1000053 / IMS:1000054 absolute position
  offset x/y).

\subsection m2data_tools_align Image Alignment

Press <b>Align Images</b> to automatically centre all visible images on the
spatial centre of the largest image.  The largest image is moved to the world
origin first; all other images are then shifted so that their centres coincide
with that reference centre.  All derived child nodes (segmentations, point sets,
normalization images) are moved by the same offset.

Press <b>Reset Alignment</b> to revert every image to its original coordinates
from the imzML metadata.

\subsection m2data_tools_scalebar Colour Bar (Scale Bar)

Enable the <b>Scale Bar</b> group box to overlay a colour bar on the axial render
window.  Select the image whose lookup table should be reflected in the colour bar
using the <b>Reference image</b> combo box inside the group box.

Adjust the annotation with:
- <b>Font Size</b> slider – size of the axis tick labels.
- <b>Orientation</b> – vertical or horizontal bar.

\section m2data_artifacts External Data and Auto-Loading

M2aia can automatically load pre-computed images and data artefacts that are placed
in the same directory as the imzML file.  The loading happens in two distinct stages
handled by different components.

\subsection m2data_artifacts_reader Stage 1 – imzML Reader (before the dataset is added to the Data Manager)

The imzML reader inspects the dataset directory at load time and silently absorbs any
of the following files if they exist.  The stem \c &lt;name&gt; must match the imzML
file name without its extension (e.g. \c sample for \c sample.imzML).

| File pattern | Effect |
|---|---|
| \c &lt;name&gt;.mask.nrrd | Tissue mask / segmentation. Loaded as a \c MultiLabelSegmentation and replaces the default empty mask. |
| \c &lt;name&gt;.shift.nrrd | Per-pixel spectral shift correction image. |
| \c &lt;name&gt;.mps | MITK point set with landmark or injection-site positions. |
| \c &lt;name&gt;.TIC.nrrd | Pre-computed TIC normalisation image. Bypasses on-the-fly TIC computation. |
| \c &lt;name&gt;.RMS.nrrd | Pre-computed RMS normalisation image. |
| \c &lt;name&gt;.Mean.nrrd | Pre-computed Mean normalisation image. |
| \c &lt;name&gt;.Median.nrrd | Pre-computed Median normalisation image. |
| \c &lt;name&gt;.&lt;type&gt;.nrrd | Any other normalisation type listed in the normalization strategy type list. |

\note The normalisation NRRD files must have exactly the same number of pixels as the
imzML dataset (number of valid spectra in the spatial grid).  Pixel type must be
\c float or \c double; 3-D images are expected.  If the size or type does not match,
a warning is logged and the file is skipped.

\b Workflow example – providing a custom TIC image:

Suppose your dataset is located at:
\code
/data/study/sample.imzML
/data/study/sample.ibd
\endcode

Create a TIC image of the same spatial dimensions using an external tool (e.g. pyM2aia)
and save it as:
\code
/data/study/sample.TIC.nrrd
\endcode

The next time you open \c sample.imzML in M2aia, the TIC normalization image is taken
directly from that file and the time-consuming per-spectrum accumulation is avoided.

\subsection m2data_artifacts_dataview Stage 2 – Data View (after the dataset appears in the Data Manager)

Once the spectrum image node has been added to the Data Manager, the Data View scans
the same directory for derived analysis result images and attaches them as hidden
child nodes:

| File pattern | Loaded as |
|---|---|
| \c &lt;name&gt;.tSNE.nrrd | t-SNE embedding image (visual output of dimensionality reduction). |
| \c &lt;name&gt;.PCA.nrrd | PCA score image. |
| \c &lt;name&gt;.UMAP.nrrd | UMAP embedding image. |
| \c &lt;name&gt;.def.nrrd | Deformation / stack index image (used by the image-stack workflow). |

These nodes are added as child nodes of the parent MSI dataset node.  They are
initially hidden (visibility \c false) and can be made visible via the Data Manager
or programmatically.

\note All of the Stage-2 files must also conform to the spatial layout of the parent
image (same width, height, and origin) so that they overlay correctly in the render
windows.

*/
